  "texts": [
    "Shen et al. [18] proposed a Q-learning-based memetic algorithm for multiobjective dynamic software project scheduling, which considers human factors such as motivation and learning ability, skill proficiency, and employee satisfaction in addition to traditional objectives like project duration, cost, robustness, and stability under practical constraints.",
    "Their algorithm learns the most appropriate global and local search methods for different software project environment states by using Q-learning.",
    "The algorithm is effective in improving convergence performance in dynamic environments, while maintaining a good distribution and spread of solutions.",
    "Maenhout and Vanhoucke [101] analysed the integrated project scheduling and personnel staffing problem for different personnel resource types.",
    "They evaluated different scheduling policies and practices and examined the impact of introducing more flexible resource types, such as overtime and temporary help."
